            <div1 type="letter" n="1" id="d5">
                <pb n="1" entity="DSSR_000000766_0227"/>
                <head>Letter from Adelaide E. Case to Charles N. Tenney, <date value="1862-11-09"
                        >November 9, 1862</date></head>


                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <name type="place">Mecca</name>
                        <date value="1862-11-09">Nov. 9<hi rend="super">th</hi> 1862</date>
                    </dateline>

                    <salute>My own darling Charlie</salute>

                </opener>

                <p> I am going to<lb/> try and write you a cheerful letter<lb/>
                    <orig reg="today">to day</orig>. I say <hi rend="underline">cheerful</hi>, and
                    mind<lb/> you if it is <hi rend="underline">not</hi>, it is no fault<lb/> of
                    mine. You will conclude and<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">rightly</hi> that I have had a <orig reg="dreadful"
                        >dread-<lb/> ful.</orig> (please excuse the division of that<lb/> word)
                    attack of the &ldquo;<orig reg="blues.">blues</orig>&rdquo; You
                    will<lb/> now wish to know the cause. Well,<lb/> as you are my <hi
                        rend="underline">confidante</hi> I will<lb/> tell <hi rend="underline"
                    >you</hi>. The first; (you <orig reg="won't">wont</orig> tell<lb/>
                    <orig reg="anybody">any-body</orig>?) I have not heard one<lb/> word from <name
                        type="person">C. M. Tenney</name>, <hi rend="underline">for</hi> <hi
                        rend="underline">almost</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">two</hi> <hi rend="underline">weeks</hi>. (listen now) and
                    when<lb/> he last wrote me, <hi rend="underline">he</hi> <hi rend="underline"
                        >was</hi> <hi rend="underline">not</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">able</hi> <hi rend="underline">to</hi> <hi rend="underline"
                        >go</hi> <hi rend="underline">with</hi> <hi rend="underline">the</hi> <hi
                        rend="underline"><abbr expan="regiment">regt</abbr>.</hi> I do so<lb/> hope
                    he is not so ill as not to<lb/> be able to write to &mdash; to &mdash;
                    Addie <pb n="2" entity="DSSR_000000766_0228"/> But what does it mean. He is
                    always<lb/> so prompt in writing when he is<lb/> not well. Can not <hi
                        rend="underline">you</hi> tell me<lb/> where he is. and how? If you can<lb/>
                    I shall be a thousand times obliged.<lb/></p>
                <p> Another,, I wish the 12th of Nov. was<lb/> pa&longs;sed. Dear Charlie, I
                    almost feel<lb/> as if instead of gaining a <hi rend="underline"
                    >brother</hi><lb/> I shall lose a <hi rend="underline">sister</hi>. I know
                    not<lb/> why I feel so but it always seems<lb/> as if sisters did not bear
                        the <del hand="h1">sam</del><lb/> same relation to each other after they<lb/>
                    are married as <orig reg="before;">before,</orig> they never<lb/> seem to give
                    each other that confi-<lb/> dence that they did before, but<lb/> I can not write
                    freely upon this<lb/> subject even to you, dear. I only wish<lb/> that you could
                    be here <hi rend="underline">then</hi>. <orig reg="That">that</orig><lb/> is if <hi
                        rend="underline">I</hi> must go and <name type="person">Laurie</name>
                    says<lb/> I <hi rend="underline">must</hi>. Here she sits now writing<lb/>
                    &ldquo;farewell letters&rdquo; &mdash; as she says &mdash; to
                    her<lb/> friends. Dear girl! She seems to look<lb/> forward with an air of
                    resignation <pb n="3" entity="DSSR_000000766_0229"/> rather than
                    happine&longs;s. Oh Charlie<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">my</hi> heart aches for <hi rend="underline">
                        <orig reg="her.">her</orig>
                    </hi> But I<lb/> will not write this to you <hi rend="underline">my own</hi>
                </p>
                <p> You are glad <name type="person">
                        <hi rend="underline">Valandingham</hi>
                    </name> was<lb/> defeated. <hi rend="underline">So</hi> <hi rend="underline"
                        >was</hi> <hi rend="underline">I</hi>. What an in<del hand="h1"
                    >s</del>&mdash;<lb/> sult to <name type="person">Chio's</name> brave soldiers
                    was the<lb/> nomination of such a man &mdash; no<lb/> not a <hi
                        rend="underline">man</hi> &mdash; a traitor as Valan-<lb/> dingham. He
                    is now &mdash; and always<lb/> has been working against us &mdash;<lb/>
                    working with all the energy of<lb/> which demons are capable to<lb/> destroy
                    this noble republic.</p>

                <p>And how many more &ldquo;Valandinghams&rdquo;<lb/> have we here <orig
                        reg="in">at</orig> the <orig reg="north?">north</orig><lb/> Treason is not
                        confined <del hand="h1">here</del>in<lb/> the south. Even here in Mecca<lb/>
                    are &ldquo;Knights of the Golden Circle&rdquo;<lb/> bound by the most
                    solemn obliga-<lb/> tions to aid the rebels in<lb/> erecting an institution the
                    chief<lb/> corner stone of which is <hi rend="underline">Slavery</hi><lb/> Shall
                    they succeed in their <pb n="4" entity="DSSR_000000766_0230"/> purposes: No.
                    never. True Freedom<lb/> and Slavery are drawing <orig reg="together">to
                    gether</orig><lb/> and will soon engage in a dread-<lb/> ful conflict. God only
                    knows which<lb/> will conquer. but we hope and<lb/> trust that America may
                    come<lb/> forth with <hi rend="underline">more</hi> than<add hand="h1"
                        place="supralinear">her</add> original<lb/> purity and have her <hi
                        rend="underline">truly</hi> <hi rend="underline">free</hi><lb/> May God be
                    with us in our<lb/> great conflict, and may we ever<lb/> look to him as our <hi
                        rend="underline">nations</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">savior</hi></p>

                <p>But you will pardon me for<lb/> not writing a longer letter will<lb/> you not
                    dearest? I must write<lb/> to <name type="person">Dora</name> <orig reg="today">to
                        day</orig>. I forgot to tell<lb/> you that I attended the funeral<lb/> of
                    Capt. L.D. Kee last <orig reg="Tuesday.">tuesday</orig> <orig reg="He"
                    >he</orig><lb/> was killed at <name type="place">Perryville</name><ref
                        target="n1" n="1">1</ref><lb/> He was buried according to the<lb/> Masonic
                    order. Laura is telling<lb/> me a good lot to write you such<lb/> as "I wish he
                    was home", "I am a<lb/> Case yet." "I've got a <unclear>hard cold</unclear>"
                    <lb/> &amp;c. &amp;c..</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>But I must bid you the<lb/> wish of success and goodbye,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="underline">Please</hi> write <hi rend="underline">very</hi> soon to
                        your own</salute>
                    <signed>Adeli</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>


        <back id="d6">

            <div1 type="notes" n="1" id="d7">
                <head>Notes</head>
                <note id="n1" place="end" n="1"><seg type="note-symbol">1</seg>
                    <p>Captain Leander Dwight Kee was killed in the battle at Perryville, Kentucky,
                        October 8, 1862. The Perryville Battle had an estimated 7,407
                    casaulties.</p>
                </note>
            </div1>
        </back>
